ODE IX.

‘ The most continuous mins, the longest winters, end at last. Let not your grief for Mystes alone be unending, Valgius. Not even Nestor grieved inconsolably for the son of his old age, nor his parents and sisters for the blooming Troilus. ’Tis time to cease from wailings more womanly than theirs, and to sing of Caesar’s triumphs.’
